Place a #foil-lined baking sheet{} on top rack (2 #baking sheets{2}, on top and middle racks, for 4 servings) and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Finely chop @Roma tomato{1}. Core, deseed, and dice @poblano pepper{1} into ¼-inch pieces. Finely chop @cilantro{¼%ounce}. Slice @jalapeño{1} into thin rounds, removing ribs and seeds for less heat.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over high heat. Add poblano and cook, stirring, until lightly charred, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground beef{10%ounce}; season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}. Keeping beef in pan, drain any excess grease. Stir in poblano, tomato, and @Southwest spice blend{2%tsp} (4 tsp for 4 servings; we'll use the rest later). Cook until tomato begins to break down, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Meanwhile, carefully place @flatbreads{2} on preheated #baking sheet{}. Drizzle both sides of flatbreads with @olive oil{2%tsp} and season with salt and pepper. Toast in oven until golden brown and crisp, ~{5-7%minutes}.

> TIP: Keep an eye out to avoid burning.

Remove toasted flatbreads from oven, then evenly top with beef mixture. Sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{½%cup} and @Monterey Jack cheese{¼%cup}. Return to oven and bake until cheese melts, about ~{2%minutes}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{4%tbsp} and remaining Southwest spice blend. Stir in @water{}, 1 tsp at a time, until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper. Drizzle flatbreads with crema and @hot sauce{1%tsp} to taste. Sprinkle with cilantro and as much sliced jalapeño as you like. Cut into slices and serve.